text.tspan: The Palmer Drought Severity Index is the most widely used index to measure drought severity over time. An index
value of zero represents the average moisture conditions observed between 1931 and 1990. Positive values mean
wetter than average, negatives mean drier than average.
Source: NOAA (National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration) via the US EPA
Note: A value between -2 and -3 indicates moderate drought, -3 to -4 is severe drought, and -4 or below indicates extreme drought.
